        "heading": "Clinical Note",
        "section_value": "Chief Complaint\nRight lower flank pain\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports right lower flank pain that began approximately 24 hours ago. He describes the pain as constant and rated it 7 out of 10. He denies fever, chills, nausea, or vomiting. He reports the pain is exacerbated by movement. He states he has a history of kidney stones and was treated with lithotripsy 3 years ago. He denies any recent trauma. He reports taking ibuprofen as needed for the pain.\nFindings\nThe patient's vital signs are stable. The right flank is tender to palpation. Urinalysis reveals hematuria. The patient's abdomen is soft and non-distended.\nAssessment\nThe patient's presentation is concerning for possible nephrolithiasis. Differential diagnoses include urinary tract infection and musculoskeletal strain.\nPlan\nOrder a urine culture and sensitivity. Order a BMP. Consider lithotripsy. Advise patient to increase fluid intake. Follow up in 24-48 hours.",
